2026-04-16 12:12:21 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Control module inverted‑cables indicator LED', 'Control module inverted‑cables indicator series resistor', 'Control module internal wiring of inverted‑cables indicator branch'] hypothesis_explanation='The control module input is confirmed to receive correct +12 V and 0 V from the power supply. Yet the output pair to the load always remains at 0 V regardless of switch position, meaning the 12 V rail inside the control module is not being delivered to the output.\n\nDirect measurement of the inverted‑cables indicator branch shows the LED has about 12 V reverse‑biased across it (0 V on the anode, ~12 V on the cathode), and the series resistor has 12 V on both ends (no drop). This indicates the indicator branch is effectively isolated and reverse biased, not forward biased or shorting the rails as designed for a normal or inverted condition.\n\nGiven that the red LED is off (consistent with reverse bias) but the module still fails to pass 12 V to the output, the most plausible fault is an internal miswire or open in the indicator branch/its connections to the main rails. For example, the cathode end (and one side of the resistor) may be incorrectly wired in series with the 12 V feed to the switch/output instead of in parallel, or there is an open trace/joint between the control‑input 12 V node and the switch/output node, possibly at the connection shared with the indicator network.\n\nThus, the fault likely resides in the control module’s inverted‑cables indicator LED/resistor branch or its associated wiring, preventing the internal 12 V node from reaching the output pair even though the input rails are correct.'
