2026-04-16 12:12:54 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=["Control Output Cable (+) port 'p' connection inside control module"] hypothesis_explanation="Measurements show that the control module input correctly receives +12 V / 0 V and that the switch path from the 12 V input node to the conductor designated Control Output Cable (+) has nominal resistance, so the internal series path itself is intact. However, the latest diagnostic reports that the port 'p' of Control Output Cable (+) is floating/disconnected from the rest of the circuit. With respect to the external terminals, this means that although the internal wiring from 12 V to the intended output conductor exists, it is not actually bonded to the output connector pin that goes to the load. As a result, both output terminals measured 0 V relative to the 0 V rail and no 12 V ever reaches the load, so the lamp cannot turn on, even though the rest of the circuit appears functional.\n\nThus the root cause is an open or miswired connection at Control Output Cable (+) port 'p' inside the control module (e.g. unsoldered/broken joint to the output connector). Repairing or reattaching this port to the internal 12 V switch node should restore proper operation of the lamp when the switch is closed."
